title: Daly Nature Reserve - Indigenous Flora and Fauna, Gisborne

items.title: Jalmenus evagoras evagoras
items.content_text: Common Imperial Blue recently emerged.  Other photos show ants attending the pupae and caterpillars.

items.title: Amanita muscaria
items.content_text: Common name Fly Agaric.  Very large specimen nearly 30cm across.

items.title: Acacia verniciflua (Bacchus Marsh variant)
items.content_text:
Acacia rostriformis (Bacchus Marsh Varnish Wattle)
Shrub 1 - 6m tall generally multi-stemmed from the base
Phyllodes narrowly elliptic to oblong elliptic 20 - 50mm long, 5 - 10mm wide, 
2 longitudinal nerves (veins) per face 
Apex of phyllode excentrically mucronate, rostriform (beaked) 
Flower heads globular, 1-3 per axil
Flowers around September

items.title: Gminatus australis
items.content_text: Lots using Acacia rostriformis as a base for their deadly activities! Note the weaponry on the head.

items.title: Orthetrum caledonicum
items.content_text: Female struggling to get airborne in the undergrowth on a relatively cool day.

items.title: Paropsis atomaria
items.content_text: Distinctive egg bundle arrangement of Paropsis species (beetle). Possibly Paropsis atomaria.

items.title: Membracidae spp.
items.content_text: Tiny, horned hopper on Black Wattle (Acacia mearnsii).

items.title: Diuris sulphurea
items.content_text: Magnificent display of Tiger Orchids at Daly Reserve this year.

items.title: Lomandra filiformis subsp. filiformis
items.content_text: Leaf 1mm wide and a little glaucous. A few plants in a reserve with heaps of subsp. coriacea. Obviously different to subsp. coriacea.

items.title: Pterostylis nutans
items.content_text: About 6 colonies found today, some comprising dozens of plants.

items.title: Jalmenus evagoras evagoras
items.content_text: Ants feeding off Imperial Blue Butterfly pupae.

items.title: Acacia pravissima
items.content_text: Not sure which wattle this is??

items.title: Caedicia simplex, Eucalyptus radiata subsp. radiata
Tryonocryptus gigas
items.content_text: Flying around just above the ground like a spider wasp.

items.title: Psoropempula erythrostethus
items.content_text: Spotted patrolling the same area as the Zebra Spider Wasp in observation 8828. ID by Ken Walker. At least half the size. This species also depicted at http://lifeunseen.com/index2_item_5399.php

items.title: Turneromyia bassiana
items.content_text: Great watching this - tapping with its tail at the covered entrance to the hole. Not sure if tapping was at its home or trying to encourage a spider out of its hole. Otherwise it was flying/patrolling low across the forest floor searching for spiders.

items.title: Acacia mearnsii
items.content_text: Saw a pair of Black Cockatoos eating seeds in the tree yesterday - see observation 8807.

items.title: Strepera versicolor
items.content_text: White wing tips and seems to lack hooked beak.

items.title: Laetiporus portentosus
items.content_text: Fallen of a Euc in the reserve.

items.title: Delta spp., Heteronympha penelope penelope
items.content_text: Location accuracy to within 100m. Daly Reserve.

items.title: Geitoneura klugii 'dark form'
items.content_text: Great camouflage. Pic 2 and 3 is the same individual.

items.title: Acacia rostriformis
items.content_text: Very hairy seedpod is an important ID feature (now A. rostriformis).

items.title: Wurmbea dioica
items.content_text: 2nd pic seems to be of an unusual bisexual plant. 1st pic is female.
